plenus: final s was so lightly pronounced that the older poets felt justified in neglecting it in their scansion. It was probably scarcely at all pronounced by the less educated Romans, since it is often wholly omitted in inscriptions and has been lost in modernItalian. Cicero Orator 161 says that the neglect to pronounce final s is ‘somewhat ’ boorish’ (subrusticum), though formerly thought very refined (polibus). Even Lucretius sometimes disregards itin his scansion. In the ordi- nary literary Latin a large number of words have lost an original s;

e. g. all the nouns of the ·a declension. Cf. 14, l. 18 consectus.
